textMap.PRIMARY: Bonus Content: This episode of "The Man In the High Castle" is one of a number of titles that benefit from exclusive videos and behind-the-scenes photos, accessible in the X-Ray Bonus tab in Prime Video.
Himmler's solemn recital of the mantra, "He alone who owns the youth, gains the future," is a direct quotation from the Adolf Hitler.

In our timeline US President Harry Truman's personal notes and letters contain references to the devious character of J. Edgar Hoover. "We want no Gestapo or secret police," he wrote in a 1945 note. "The FBI is trending in that direction. They are dabbling in sex-life scandals and plain blackmail." In a letter to his wife, Truman wrote, "J. Edgar Hoover would give his right eye to take over, and all congressmen and senators are afraid of him."

According to Chelah Horsdal, it was freeing to perform the scene at the psychotherapist's office without having the camera pointed directly at her. Nevertheless, she did feel pressure to produce tears from her right eye, so the camera would be able capture it from its unique angle.

The creative team for Season 3 loved the idea of bringing J. Edgar Hoover into the narrative of "The Man in the High Castle" because he's a character from history whose real-world persona fits seamlessly into the alt-history world.
Female homosexuality would not have been viewed as being as transgressive as male sexuality in the Greater Nazi Reich. However, it was still a punishable offense.

Throughout "The Man in the High Castle" characters are sometimes heard referring to the Japanese as "Pons." This term is a truncation of the Japanese word 'Nippon,' which means 'Japan.' In the alt-timeline it is most often used as a slur. Also with the Japanese accent in speaking English when one is pronouncing "Japan" or "Japanese" it sounds like "Jah-Pon" and "Jah-Pon-eeze", which is also where the term could derive from - presuming one did not know that "Nippon" means Japan. However this is an unlikely event considering the amount of Japanese language and culture that has melded its' way into American culture in the alternative timeline we see in "The Man In The High Castle".

In our history, J. Edgar Hoover was born, raised and died in Washington D.C. In the alt-timeline the American capital was raised to the ground by the Nazi A Bomb in December, 1945, which means a strange twist of fate must have provided Hoover with a reason to leave D.C. so that he could rise to power in the 1960s world of "The Man in the High Castle."

According to Rufus Sewell, who plays John Smith, the scene in which John is confronted by Reichsmarshall Rockwell, while Himmler and Hoover look on, was difficult to play; he had to moderate his reactions in the moment, his response could not be a straight-forward reply to Rockwell's accusations.

John Smith's greatest joy and greatest weakness is his family. His relentless pursuit of power and his upward trajectory through the ranks of the American Reich is almost entirely motivated by his need to protect his wife and children.
John and Helen have been married for 18 years.

George Lincoln Rockwell, in our timeline, was murdered by a disgruntled former member of his party in 1967. The Party is the American Nazi Party - founded in March 1959. Originally named World Union of Free Enterprise National Socialists, it was renamed the American Nazi Party in December 1959.

The black pin bearing what appears to be an upside-down CND symbol, is the pin worn by proud Lebensborn children in "The Man in the High Castle." The symbol is, in fact, a representation of the Elhaz rune. In history, the Elhaz rune was appropriated by the Nazis as the official iconography of the Lebensborn project.
According to series creatives, the sequence in Joe's hotel room at the end of Episode 305 is clear proof that the Nazi re-education (torture and systematic psyops) worked on him.

Much like in the TV series, in Philip K. Dick's book, Joe Cinnadella dies at the hands of Juliana after she slashes his neck in a hotel room. In the book, however, Joe has a short conversation with Juliana prior to dying; he pleads with her for help as he clasps onto his neck for dear life. Juliana's response is detached and emotionally inappropriate, suggesting a great depth of trauma has resulted from her actions.
